'But following the transfer of the funds, the defendant failed to send the snooker cue or make any arrangements for the modifications to be carried out as agreed,' Ms Hewitt told the court.

'When there was no sign of the snooker cue, a report was made to the police. They carried out an investigation and arrested the defendant. The defendant was still using the cue as his own personal property.'

Mr Shek made a formal complaint to police on January 24 this year, after the promised John Parris Ultimate cue failed to arrive.

Ms Hewitt said Lee had promised to send the cue along with letters of authenticity from himself and John Parris.

'Mr Shek received an email from the defendant saying he was going to personally deliver it to Hong Kong,' Ms Hewitt said. The email read: 'If you want the cue, you need to drop the charges and I will sign some pictures for you', the prosecutor added.

