'We also note that you are on benefits and your income is significantly lower.'

Lee was fined £110 for the offence and told to pay Mr Shek £1,600 in compensation, along with £85 prosecution costs and a £20 victim surcharge.

Mr Fryer asked Lee if he would be able to pay the total £1,815 to the court following the hearing.Lee, wearing a black jacket, black T-shirt and jeans, replied: 'I can’t pay that today, no.'

Mr Fryer added: 'It will be deducted from your benefits on a weekly basis. We will also make a collection order, which means if the payments stop, someone will be knocking on your door.'

Lee did not comment as he left the court.

